Question 5

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Data Types in C

Consider the following function declaration

int* f(int *);

Which of the following is correct about the declaration??


f is a function which takes integer pointer as argument and returns integer.

f is a function which takes an integer pointer as an argument and returns the address of an integer.

Correct answer

f is a pointer to a function which takes integer pointer as an argument and returns integer.

f is a pointer to a function which takes an integer pointer as an argument and returns the address of an integer.

Solution

Hide

The correct declaration for (a) is int f (int *)

The correct declaration for (b) is int* f(int *);

The correct declaration for (c) is int (*f) (int *)

The correct declaration for (d) is int *(*f) (int *)


Question 6

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Types of Hash Functions

Limitations of Direct Address Table are:

Prior knowledge of maximum key value

Practically useful only if the maximum value is very less.

It causes wastage of memory space if there is a significant difference between total records and maximum value.

All of these

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Direct Address Table is a data structure that has the capability of mapping records to their corresponding keys using arrays. In direct address tables, records are placed using their key values directly as indexes. They facilitate fast searching, insertion and deletion operations.

Limitations:

Prior knowledge of maximum key value

Practically useful only if the maximum value is very less.

It causes wastage of memory space if there is a significant difference between total records and maximum value.

Hashing can overcome these limitations of direct address tables.

Question 9

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Implementing Stack Using Arrays, Linked Lists

Consider a stack S with elements in bottom-up order 1, 0, 2, 4, 5, 7 with the top of the stack as 7 and two queues Q1 and Q2. Q1 contains elements 3, 6, 7, 8, 9, 0 in that order from front to rear and Q2 is initially empty. What are the contents of Q1 and Q2 if we execute the following code??

void main( )

{

int x, y;

while (!empty (S))

{

x = pop (S);

y = dequeue (Q1);

x = x + y;

enqueue (Q1, x); // insert element ‘x’ into rear of the queue Q1

enqueue (Q2, y); // insert element ‘y’ into rear of the queue Q2

}

}


Correct answer

None of the above

Solution

Hide

The program dequeues the element from Q1 and also pops the element from stack S and stores them in x and y respectively. Then the value of y and x gets added into x.

The element dequeued from Q1 is enqueued in queue Q2

And the result of addition x is enqueued into Q1, hence Q1 has all added values and Q2 has elements from Q1, therefore the correct answer is a)

Operations on Queue

If the elements 8, 7, 5, 6, 9, 2 are inserted into the queue in that order and if an element can be deleted at any time from the queue, which of the following permutations can be obtained as the output of the queue??

7 6 5 2 9 8

8 7 5 6 9 2

Correct answer

8 9 7 6 5 2

9 7 2 5 6 8

Solution

Hide

Queue data structure function on FIFO (First In First Out). Hence the permutations 7 6 5 2 9 8 and 9 7 2 5 6 8 are not possible as the first element that will be deleted from the queue is 8 and similarly the permutation 8 9 7 6 5 2 is also not possible since the second element that will be deleted from the queue is 7.

Question 12

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Uses of Linked List

Consider the following C code:


struct Object{

int value;

struct Object *ptr;

};

void main(){

Object* A=NULL;

Object* temp =(Object*) malloc(sizeof(Object));

(*temp).value=10;

(*temp).ptr=NULL;

A=temp;


Object* temp =(Object*) malloc(sizeof(Object));

temp->value=20;

temp->ptr=NULL;

Object* temp1 = A;

while (temp1->ptr!=NULL){

temp1=temp1->ptr;

}

temp1-> ptr= temp;


}

Choose the correct statement about the above code: [MSQ]


The code will give a run time error.

Code will create a linked list and insert 2 nodes in the linked list.

Correct answer

The code will insert a node in an empty linked list and then it adds one more element at the end of the linked list.

Correct answer

The code can add more than 2 elements at the end of the linked list.

Solution

Hide

// Declaring data structure to store a node

struct Object{

int value;

struct Object *ptr;

};


void main(){

//Creating an empty linked list which has a head of name A.

Object* A=NULL;


//allocating memory to a node which is pointed by temp

Object* temp =(Object*) malloc(sizeof(Object));


//Storing 10 to data part of the node

(*temp).value=10;


//The ptr is pointing to NULL; this mean we created a single node pointed by temp

(*temp).ptr=NULL;


// A is storing address pointed by temp, hence A is pointing to the first and the only node of the linked list

A=temp;


//allocating memory for new node which is pointed by temp again

Object* temp =(Object*) malloc(sizeof(Object));


//data and ptr values initialised

temp->value=20;

temp->ptr=NULL;


//Creating a new pointer pointing to first node of the linked list

Object* temp1 = A;


//Traversing the linked list from starting to the end of linked list (here, 1st node) using temp1 pointer

while (temp1->ptr!=NULL){

temp1=temp1->ptr;

}

//Once you reach to the last node of the LL, assigning address of newly created (2nd node) to the last node of the LL

temp1-> ptr= temp;


}

BST Properties

If n elements are sorted in a binary search tree. What would be the asymptotic complexity to search a key in the tree? (Consider the BST to be skewed)

O(1)

O(log n)

O(n)

Correct answer

O(n log n)

Solution

Hide

If the binary search tree is skewed, it requires O(n) time in the worst case to search a key. If it is balanced BST, then the worst case time complexity would be O(log n).

Question 16

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Pointers and Addresses

What will be the output of following 4 lines of codes??


const char* p = "Hello";

printf ("%c ", *p);

printf ("%c ", *++p);  

printf ("%c ", *p++);  

printf ("%c ", *p);

H e e l

Correct answer

H e l l

H e l o

H H e l

Solution

Hide

const char* p = "Hello";

printf ("%c ", *p); // points to the first character in the string i.e 'H' 

printf ("%c ", *++p); // value of ++p is 'e' after the increment

printf ("%c ", *p++); // value of p++ is 'e'; // value of p has been incremented as a side effect of p++


Program declares p as a pointer to char. When we say "pointer to a char", what does that mean?? It means that the value of p is the address of a char; p tells us where in memory there is some space set aside to hold a char.


The statement also initializes p to point to the first character in the string literal "Hello". For the sake of this exercise, it's important to understand p as pointing not to the entire string, but only to the first character, 'H'. After all, p is a pointer to one char, not to the entire string. The value of p is the address of the 'H' in "Hello".


const char* p = "Hello";

printf ("%c ", *p); // prints value pointed by pointer p i.e. H

printf ("%c ", *++p); // preincrement and * has same precedence and ++ and * are right to left associative, hence value of ++p is 'e' after the increment

printf ("%c ", *p++); // post increment has higher precedence than *. But, the value of p++ is the value of p before the increment. So *p++, will be value before increment i.e. 'e'.

            // After execution of the above statement the value will be incremented now and p will be pointing to the index location of 'l'.

printf ("%c ", *p); // The current pointer value pointed by p is 'l'.

Data Types in C

What is the output of the following program??

#include<stdio.h>

#include<string.h>

int main()

{

char *a="CLOUDS";

char *b="GATERAUDRA2022";

char *r=a;

char *s=b;

printf("%s", b+1[r]-9[s]);

printf("%d", (int) strlen(b+1[r]-1[s]));

return 0;

}


0223

Correct answer

222

20225

223

Solution

Hide

1[r] = r[1] = ‘L’ 

1[s] = s[1] = ‘A’

b+ 1[r]-9[s] = b + 11

And hence the string after the 11th index is 022 in b, whose length is 3.

Hence final answer will be 0223.


#include<stdio.h>

#include<string.h>

int main()

{

char *a="CLOUDS";

char *b="GATERAUDRA2022";

char *r=a;

char *s=b;

//printf("%s", b+1[r]-9[s]);

printf("%c\n", 1[r]);  //L

printf("%c\n", 9[s]); //A

printf("%d\n", 1[r]-9[s]); //11

printf("%s", b+1[r]-9[s]); //b+11 => 022

printf("%d", (int) strlen(b+1[r]-1[s])); => 3

return 0;

}


Question 18

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Data Types in C

What is the output of the following program, if the machine has size of float, double and long double as 4, 8 and 16 bytes respectively.

#include "stdio.h"

#define PI 3.14

int main()

{

printf("%d",sizeof(PI));

return 0;

}


4

8

Correct answer

16

None

Solution

Hide

In C language, we have three floating data types i.e. float, double and long double. And the exact size of each of these 3 types depends on the C compiler implementation/platform. In the given question it is 4, 8, 16 bytes.


#define PI 3.14


Now if we do sizeof(PI), for floating constants, C standard (C11 i.e. ISO/IEC 9899:2011) has given guidelines. As per C11 clause 6.4.4.2, “An unsuffixed floating constant has type double. If suffixed by the letter f or F, it has type float. If suffixed by the letter l or L, it has type long double.“


It means the type of a floating constant is the same as that of double data type. So if size of a double on a machine is 8 bytes, the size of floating constant would be 8 bytes


Question 19

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Data Types in C

Consider the following program


int fun(int *p, int m)

{

if(m < = 1) return 0;

else return max(fun(p + 1, m – 1), p[0] – p[1]);

}


int main( )

{

int q[ ] = {10, 11, 12, 13, 14};

printf(“%d”, fun(q, 4));

}


Let assume max(x, 4) returns the maximum of x and 4. The value printed by this program is


-1

0

Correct answer

1

4

Solution

Hide

Let the base address of the array q be 100, p is pointing to the first element of q initially. We keep on moving to the next element and performing the operations of fun().

= max(max(max(fun(p + 1, 1), -1), -1),-1)

= max(max(max(0, -1), -1), -1)

= max(max(0, -1), -1)

= max(0, -1)

= 0

BST Properties

Consider the following binary search tree given below, which node contains the seventh smallest element ?

L

I

J

Correct answer

N

Solution

Hide

The In-order traversal of a binary search tree, the left left-subtree is visited first, then root and then the right sub-tree. We should always remember that every node may represent a subtree itself. If a binary tree is traversed in-order, the output will produce sorted key values in ascending order. So seventh smallest element is ‘J’﻿

So In-order traversal is A C E G H I J L N P S T

Question 25

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Introduction and Types of Heaps

Find out the data structure which will satisfy both the requirements and provides the best solution to store integers such that it should be done in O(log n) time.


I : "Deletion of the smallest element"

II: "Insertion of an element if it is not present"


Max Heap Tree

Binary search tree

Max Heap Tree or Binary search tree can be used.

Neither Max Heap Tree nor Binary search tree

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Let us try with first condition


Max heap tree: As it is max heap then smallest element may be present at leaf and leaf nodes can be n/2 if n is the total no of nodes. Then worst case will be O(n) to find smallest element in max heap and for insertion it takes O(log n) time


Binary search tree: In BST left node is less than or equal to root. So smallest element must be present on the left side. Traverse the node from root to left recursively until left is NULL. The node whose left is NULL is the node with minimum value. Worst case when BST is left skewed: O(n)


so first condition itself fails, answer is none

Pointers and Addresses

Consider the following C program

# include<stdio.h>

main( )

{

static char *m[ ] = {“children”, “letter”, “book”, “oracle”}

char **p[ ] = {m+3, m+2, m+1, m}, ***n;

n = p;

++n;

printf(“%s”, *--*++n + 3)

}

What will be the output printed??


tter

cle

ldren

Correct answer

book

Solution

Hide

printf(“%s”, *- - * ++n+3); the expression *++p evaluated because it gets value (m+1) now pre-decrement is executed, and we get (m+1) – 1 = m. The pointer now gets the value from the array of m, and adds 3 to the starting address.﻿

So output is ‘ldren’

AVL Tree

Consider the following statements

Which of the statements are true?? [MSQ]

For representing hierarchical relationship between elements, trees are efficient data structures

Correct answer

Only for root node the height of its left subtree and right subtree differ at most by 1 in AVL Tree

In-order and level order traversal of the tree will yield a sorted listing of elements of tree in Binary search tree

The minimum number of queues required to implement a priority queue is two.

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

1.Trees are efficient data structures for representing hierarchical relationship between elements,

2. For every node the height of its left subtree and right subtree differ almost by 1 in AVL Tree, it should satisfy for every node not only at the root

Question 31

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
BST Properties

The number of different Unlabeled Binary Trees can be there with 4 nodes are ____ . [NAT]

14

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

For example, let T(n) be count for n nodes.

T(0) = 1 [There is only 1 empty tree]

T(1) = 1

T(2) = 2


T(3) = T(0)*T(2) + T(1)*T(1) + T(2)*T(0) = 1*2 + 1*1 + 2*1 = 5


T(4) = T(0)*T(3) + T(1)*T(2) + T(2)*T(1) + T(3)*T(0)

     = 1*5 + 1*2 + 2*1 + 5*1 

     = 14 

Question 32

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
BST Properties

How many labeled Binary Trees can be there with 3 nodes??

14

30

Correct answer

24

18

Solution

Hide

To count labeled trees, we can use above count for unlabeled trees. 

   T(n) = (2n)! / (n+1)!n!


Here, every unlabeled tree with n nodes can create n! different labeled trees by assigning different permutations of labels to all nodes.


Therefore,


Number of Labeled Tees = (Number of unlabeled trees) * n!

                                        = [(2n)! / (n+1)!n!] × n!

For example for n = 3, there are 5 * 3! = 5*6 = 30 different labeled trees
